text:
Another big advantage is when using CTE's for inserting/updating records in multiple rows (One-to-one, or one-to-mamy), you can use the returned id in the other queries. 
Mutiple modifications in a single query reduce overall latency from a code perspective.
Moreover, a CTE is executed as a transaction, so you won't need to start/commit a transaction in your code.

author: Anwar Pasha

text:
I doubt that runs faster than the derived query.  CTE almost always results in worse performance and in this instance I wouldn't use it I would instead do this \/

SELECT t.* FROM 
	(SELECT s.storeid
		,SUM(s.Cost) OVER(PARTITION BY s.storeid) as Total
		,AVG(s.Cost) OVER(PARTITION BY s.storeid) as Average 
	FROM Sales s
	) t
WHERE t.total > t.Average

From a performance standpoint I almost NEVER see CTE have improvements except in rare cases where you have to use it over and over again.  The only time I use CTE is for recursion and that performance is pretty bad as well but it is the best way to do recursion......That being said the performance shouldn't be that much worse and if this helps you organize your code and everyone in your organization does it this way it is the correct way to do it.....Kind of a personal preference thing.... Good explanation of how it works though I just won't use it in this instance.

author: Stefan Todorovikj

text:
Query 1:
a subquery works too:
SELECT * FROM employee
WHERE salary >
(SELECT AVG(salary) as avg_sal FROM employee)

or I can simplify the CTE as:
WITH avg_sal as (
SELECT *, AVG(salary) as avg_salary FROM employee
)
SELECT * FROM avg_sal
WHERE salary >  avg_salary

Query 2:
WITH total_sales as (
SELECT store_id, sum(cost) as total_sales_per_store
FROM sales
GROUP BY store_id
)
SELECT *, AVG(total_sales_per_store) as avg_sales_across_all_store
FROM total_sales
WHERE total_sales_per_store > avg_sales_across_all_store 

OR

SELECT *, AVG(total_sales_per_store) as avg_sales_across_all_store
FROM
(
SELECT store_id, sum(cost) as total_sales_per_store
FROM sales
GROUP BY store_id
)
WHERE total_sales_per_store > avg_sales_across_all_store

author: RAVI TEJA BALLA

text:
Hi Laura,
Are you talking about the below query:

select *
from   (select s.store_id, sum(s.cost) as total_sales_per_store
				from sales s
				group by s.store_id
	   ) total_sales
join   (select cast(avg(total_sales_per_store) as int) avg_sale_for_all_store
				from (select s.store_id, sum(s.cost) as total_sales_per_store
		  	  		from sales s
			  			group by s.store_id) x
	   ) avg_sales
on total_sales.total_sales_per_store > avg_sales.avg_sale_for_all_store;


If yes, then in PostgreSQL, every subquery in the FROM clause needs to have an alias.
In this query with the FROM clause (the JOIN table), I have used a query which has a subquery inside it. 
Meaning there are 2 sub queries within this JOIN table hence we need to have an alias to both these subqueries hence i have an "x" for the inner subquery and alias as "avg_sales" for the outer query.

Hope this clarifies.

text:
When you write a query with just SELECT clause then it‚Äôs kind of like hard coding that value.. 

Like in PostgreSQL if you want to fetch today‚Äôs date then you write query like 
SELECT CURRENT_DATE 

In oracle, same query can be written as 
SELECT 1 FROM dual ‚Äî> returns 1

Or 

SELECT SYSDATE FROM dual ‚Äî> returns current date 

We generally use this to return some static value ..

May be in future if am making basic SQL tutorial playlist then will consider to talk abt this query as well..

Thank you for the suggestion though üôèüèº
